Backed by results of tests conducted by Vietnam’s top environmental experts, farmers in Dong Nai, Ba Ria–Vung Tau, and Ho Chi Minh City have demanded payment of VND119.6 billion ($6.26 million), VND53.6 billion ($2.8 million), and VND45.74 billion ($2.4 million), respectively (

ThanhNien News 2010a). In their response, Vedan offered to pay a fraction of the requested amounts and worded the package as subsidies to maintain good relationship with the communities as well as honor its corporate social responsibility. The company initially started at VND7 billion to Dong Nai, then raised to VND15 billion, and later to VND30 billion. For Ba Ria–Vung Tau, the package was offered at VND6 billion and later raised to VND10 billion. Farmers in Ho Chi Minh City were offered VND7 billion initially, then VND12 billion, and later VND16 billion. Frustrated, governmental and provincial officials called for a class action by the affected residents against the Taiwanese polluter. By early August 2010, over 5,000 individual petitions have been filed to local People’s Courts in all three provinces (see Figure 2
). Facing what was potentially the most high-profile lawsuit against a foreign investor in Vietnam, Vedan finally backed down. On August 17, 2010, Vedan agreed to an out-of-court payout of VND210 billion ($10.7 million) to farmers in the three affected provinces to be paid in two installments. A contractual agreement was inked between Vedan and local authorities documenting the payout amount and schedule, prompting a withdrawal of petitions (
ThanhNien News 2010b; see Figure 3
).

The authors believe that the local authorities and Vietnam’s Ministry of Resources and Environment should take full responsibility to the Vietnamese public for the killing of the Thi Vai river. Vedan was an exemplary success of the open door policy attracting foreign investors to Vietnam. Vedan entered Vietnam as early as 1991, even before the US trade embargo on Vietnam was lifted, and started operating its first production facilities in 1994. Over the course of fourteen years (until the case was uncovered in 2008), the Vietnam plant had become Vedan’s largest MSG manufacturing plant in the world. Vedan received many benefits offered to a major investor, such as tax breaks, low rent, and loose supervision from governing authorities. In Vietnam, Vedan has been fined four times for violation of environmental standards and by Vietnamese laws, three strikes means shutdown. In 1997, environmental scientists conducted several tests and concluded that the segment of the Thi Vai river where Vedan’s plant is located was heavily polluted. However, there was no penalty or investigation, because Vedan was a major purchaser of raw materials (cassava) grown by local farmers. After having repeatedly violated Vietnamese environmental standards, on April 23, 2008, Vedan still received a five-year permit from the Ministry of Resources and Environment to discharge wastewater into the Thi Vai river. In October 2009, Vedan Vietnam received the “2009 Product Safety for the Community’s Health” award granted by the Ho Chi Minh City branch office of the Ministry of Science and Technology in collaboration with Natusi, a quality and branding consultancy (see Figure 5
). This award was later revoked by said authority, citing an “administrative” error (

The Saigon Times 2010).
